                    </div>
                    <span>When first introduced to this book, I was highly skeptical. After all, I have already read many religious, spiritual and philosophical texts. Reading used to fulfill me momentarily, as there was a gradual "let-down" as spiritual sensations became "medusa"d into cold stone intellectual mind-stuff. This book was able to point past itself, allowed me to watch myself inspite of mind-stuff, and to be able to find peace in the present moment.  Practicing the Power of Now, as the title suggests, is more condensed and instruction-oriented than the Power of Now.  People have asked me which one to recommend first.  I guess you just have to go with feeling.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">We're Always Practicing 'Now'</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-26</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Thinking that I could learn something new about myself and the ability to 'practice' living in the Now, I realized I'm always living in the Now. It comes with realization and if this book helps someone, that's wonderful, but it didn't help me. I already practice living in the presence of God and God is always in the Now. 
<br />
<br />Tolle's descriptions of the mind and of meditation may be great for others who are just starting out on a personal journey of finding Truth. The mental aspects of the mind can be programmed and this book, I think, expounds on that premise.
<br />
<br />Gail Gupton, Author, 'The 31-Day Diet of Spiritual Enlightenment'</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Did nothing for me</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>4</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-07</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>When I read this book, I found it to be very true. But I have never managed to integrate it into my daily life. I have tried just to do nothing, be present, and it tires me. It seems to me that his method of finding peace is to force it. It also seems to me to be a very apathetic way of life.
<br />
<br />I do not think this book is all crap, but it is way too extreme to be adapted for most humans. Of course it is good to be present, and not to be concerned too much about the past and future, but I rather suggest something in between what "normal" people do and Tolle's teachings, than to take things to its extremes.
<br />
<br />As many already have mentioned, this book is a repetitive zen ripoff. For people who are not familiar with this kind of books, I suggest reading something a little less extreme. This book can be dangerous.
<br />
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A fantastic contribution to humanity</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
